\begin_body

\begin_layout Abstract
In programming, there are three dependency types: data dependency, control
 dependency and source code dependency.
 The two last dependency types are known as ones that can be inverted to
 the favor of the application.
 In enforcing the data dependencies, it become unpredictable to use the
 two inversion types together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
However, according to the current comprehension, when they are taken together,
 the application's data dependencies became unpredictable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Taking them together means to 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
—————-
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Our goal is to facilitate Excel-like formulas in objects' classes.
 Therefore we combine the 
\emph on
reactive variable
\emph default
 from Functional Reactive Programming with the
\emph on
 instance variable
\emph default
 from Object Oriented Programming.
 The new concept is named 
\emph on
RIVar
\emph default
, a shortcut to 
\emph on
Reactive Instance Variable
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Reactive variables by their nature suffer from cycles, glitches and reassigments.
 Current approaches include: avoidance, iterations, and central management.
 However, when combining reactive variables with instance variables in OOP
 -- RIVars are subject to unsupported constructions, unpredictable results,
 and no-isolation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
We suggest that RIVar will support 
\emph on
multiple assignment
\emph default
, and that RIVar values over time will be an observable stream.
 Then RIVar with several inputs will have its varying value from executing
 a 
\emph on
merge
\emph default
 operator over its inputs' streams.
\end_layout

